Package io.github.pranavavva.pokejavaapi

Class Pokemon

java.lang.Object
io.github.pranavavva.pokejavaapi.Pokemon
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable
public abstract class Pokemon
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
The Pokemon abstract class provides a foundation for Type-specific Pokemon concrete classes. Pokemon can have one or two Types. type1 will never be null, whereas type2 may be null if the Pokemon only has one Type. The fields, health, attack, defense, spAttack, spDefense, and speed are used in battle. The values in a Pokemon object represent the "base" stat at Pokemon Lvl. 100. These base stats can have modifiers applied to them (for example, as a by-product of Moves, Abilities, or Items), however the value in the class itself may never be directly changed. The effect of modifiers are accounted for in the damage calculation equation. The attack and defense fields are used in calcultaing damage caused MoveCategory.PHYSICAL moves. spAttack and spDefense are used in calculating damage caused by MoveCategory.SPECIAL moves. speed is used in determining which Pokemon uses their chosen Move first in a turn. NOTE: Some moves may be listed as Type.PHYSICAL but may actually cause damage using special stats. The fields move1, move2, move3, and move4 contain references to the Moves the Pokemon knows and can use in battle. Currently, these fields hold the actual move object, however in the future, it may hold a database ID number to the Move it references, to better facilitate storing Pokemon and Moves in a database.
See Also:
Type, Move, MoveCategory, Serialized Form

  • Constructor Details

    • Pokemon

      public Pokemon​(java.lang.String name, Type type1, Type type2, int health, int attack, int defense, int spAttack, int spDefense, int speed, Move move1, Move move2, Move move3, Move move4)
      The Pokemon object constructor requires all 13 fields to be known in advance. At this point in time, the constructor accepts the actual Move object for move1, move2, move3, and move4, however in the future, it will change to accept a database ID number to better facilitate storing Pokemon and Moves in a database. This version of the Pokemon constructor requries the actual Move object as an argument. A future constructor will accept database references for the Moves. The battle stats for the Pokemon (health, attack, defense, spAttack, spDefense, and speed) are the corresponding values of the in-game Pokemon at Lvl. 100. This information must be taken from Bulbapedia.
      Parameters:
      name - The name of the Pokemon
      type1 - The first (or main) Type of the Pokemon. This field may not be null.
      type2 - The second Type of the Pokemon. If the Pokemon has only one Type, this field may be null.
      health - The health (HP) of the Pokemon at Lvl. 100.
      attack - The physical attack stat of the Pokemon at Lvl. 100. This is used to determine damage dealt by a MoveCategory.PHYSICAL Move.
      defense - The physical defense stat of the Pokemon at Lvl. 100. This is used to determine damage received by a MoveCategory.DEFENSE Move.
      spAttack - The special attack stat of the Pokemon at Lvl. 100. This is used to determine damage dealt by a MoveCategory.SPECIAL Move.
      spDefense - The special defense stat of the Pokemon at Lvl. 100. This is used to determine damage received by a MoveCategory.SPECIAL Move.
      speed - The speed of the Pokemon at Lvl. 100. This is only used to determine which Pokemon moves first in a battle turn. While speed can be affected by Moves and/or Items, it doesn't affect the damage dealt or received.
      move1 - The first Move the Pokemon knows.
      move2 - The second Move the Pokemon knows.
      move3 - The third Move the Pokemon knows.
      move4 - The fourth Move the Pokemon knows.
